The retired Navy Reserve commander served active duty in three wars, including WWII, the Korean War and the Vietnam War. He was also an NYPD detective. He has written a book about his life and members of the Heritage Springs golf community is organizing a golf tournament to honor his service and to solicit money to donate to the Wounded Warrior Project.

Amie Norquist sits with her children Allie, Ethan, Elise and Jason on a mattress serving as a couch in the living of their new home in Riverview on Thursday, Jan. 24, 2019. After a month of living in on-base housing at MacDill Air Force Base, Norquist noticed her children were getting sick, especially her youngest children Ethan and her three-year-old daughter Elise. They both developed respiratory problems and inflammation. Soon after Amie, her husband and her two oldest children Allie and Jason started experiencing similar symptoms. Soon mold was discovered. The family claims the private company running the housing did little to solve the problem. The Norquist family was forced to move off base. Like the Norquists, ten additional families have come forward having experienced the same problem with the base. Norquist said there are still many families that are afraid to come forward. “When you’re messing with my kids,” Norquist said. “I’m not going anywhere.” [Times photo by Bronte Wittpenn]

Photos of Gillum's trip in NYC. Andrew Gillum, Adam Corey Undercover FBI agents were the ones who gave Tallahassee Mayor Andrew Gillum a ticket to the Broadway show Hamilton during a trip to New York City in 2016, according to a trove of records given to the ethics commission and released to the public today. Text messages between Gillum and former lobbyist Adam Corey, who arranged outings with undercover agents looking into city corruption, were among more than 100 pages of records Corey gave the ethics commission, which is investigating trips to Costa Rica and New York that Gillum took in 2016. Corey's lawyer, Chris Kise, released the records today, just two weeks before the election, because the state ethics commission issued a subpoena for the records just last week.

Amie Norquist sits with her children Allie, Ethan, Elise and Jason on a mattress serving as a couch in the living of their new home in Riverview on Thursday, Jan. 24, 2019. After a month of living in on-base housing at MacDill Air Force Base, Norquist noticed her children were getting sick, especially her youngest children Ethan and her three-year-old daughter Elise. They both developed respiratory problems and inflammation. Soon after Amie, her husband and her two oldest children Allie and Jason started experiencing similar symptoms. Soon mold was discovered. The family claims the private company running the housing did little to solve the problem. The Norquist family was forced to move off base. Like the Norquists, ten additional families have come forward having experienced the same problem with the base. Norquist said there are still many families that are afraid to come forward. “When you’re messing with my kids,” Norquist said. “I’m not going anywhere.” [Times photo by Bronte Wittpenn]

Photos of Gillum's trip in NYC. Andrew Gillum, Adam Corey Undercover FBI agents were the ones who gave Tallahassee Mayor Andrew Gillum a ticket to the Broadway show Hamilton during a trip to New York City in 2016, according to a trove of records given to the ethics commission and released to the public today. Text messages between Gillum and former lobbyist Adam Corey, who arranged outings with undercover agents looking into city corruption, were among more than 100 pages of records Corey gave the ethics commission, which is investigating trips to Costa Rica and New York that Gillum took in 2016. Corey's lawyer, Chris Kise, released the records today, just two weeks before the election, because the state ethics commission issued a subpoena for the records just last week.
Credit/Source: Photos of Gillum's trip in NYC.
